00:26:39.540 --> 00:26:41.940
I've got a very grumpy
looking dog on this slide,

00:26:42.151 --> 00:26:43.321
got wild hair,

00:26:43.771 --> 00:26:46.200
and this is how I feel
when I review documents that have

00:26:46.200 --> 00:26:47.580
inaccessible link text.

00:26:48.181 --> 00:26:50.789
We often see, "Click here,
read more information,"

00:26:50.790 --> 00:26:53.401
used in isolation
with no surrounding context.

00:26:54.211 --> 00:26:57.180
Screen reader users often will bring up
a list of links to navigate

00:26:57.180 --> 00:27:00.780
through the content and having
link text like that is really unhelpful

00:27:00.781 --> 00:27:03.631
and doesn't tell the user
where they're going to be taken.

00:27:03.780 --> 00:27:07.890
Make sure you don't use full URLs
and just make your link text descriptive.

00:27:10.440 --> 00:27:13.500
Finally on Word documents,
just don't forget that designing

00:27:13.501 --> 00:27:15.810
for neurodiversity is often overlooked.

00:27:16.380 --> 00:27:18.721
I've got a dog image
on this slide of a black Labrador

00:27:18.721 --> 00:27:21.221
with big brown eyes
looking lovingly at the camera,

00:27:22.140 --> 00:27:24.211
and the words read, "Don't forget me."

00:27:24.870 --> 00:27:27.661
That's trying to signify that although,
we haven't covered everything

00:27:27.661 --> 00:27:28.661
in this section,

00:27:28.800 --> 00:27:31.770
things like using
plain English, don't use bold,

00:27:31.771 --> 00:27:36.509
italics, or underline in big amounts,
and making sure you're checking

00:27:36.510 --> 00:27:39.050
your color contrast, is
all still really important

00:27:39.310 --> 00:27:41.810
even if we haven't mentioned
it specifically today.

00:27:44.671 --> 00:27:46.531
Moving on as time is ticking,

00:27:46.560 --> 00:27:48.910
we're going to talk
about polished presentations

00:27:49.341 --> 00:27:52.470
and what we can do
in a presentation format to make sure

00:27:52.471 --> 00:27:53.471
they're accessible.

00:27:56.661 --> 00:27:58.411
Use the master slide.

00:27:59.341 --> 00:28:02.866
Slide master or the master
slide create accessible layouts

00:28:02.896 --> 00:28:05.310
and ensure consistency
across your presentation.

00:28:06.931 --> 00:28:11.279
If you're using Microsoft PowerPoint,
you can view the slide master under

00:28:11.280 --> 00:28:15.480
the View tab but all software
will have a version of a master layout.

00:28:16.321 --> 00:28:18.510
Make sure your master layout
is accessible,

00:28:18.511 --> 00:28:20.040
so make sure the colors work.

00:28:20.130 --> 00:28:24.660
If you're using any logos or anything,
they are also accessible but it's really,

00:28:24.661 --> 00:28:28.170
really important to make sure
that you do use that within your slides.

00:28:30.871 --> 00:28:34.801
Sections are also a nice way
in a presentation to give it structure.

00:28:35.331 --> 00:28:37.381
If you've got a particularly
long presentation,

00:28:37.381 --> 00:28:41.069
adding sections can be a nice way
to split the information

00:28:41.070 --> 00:28:43.439
into several different topic areas,
and again,

00:28:43.440 --> 00:28:46.725
the user can then navigate to the bits
that they maybe want to read more about

00:28:46.725 --> 00:28:50.101
or go back to and revisit sections
they were unsure about.

00:28:51.307 --> 00:28:55.980
It's similar to how a table of contents
might help to break up content.

00:28:56.571 --> 00:28:59.910
Again, it's really important to think
about that when you're creating

00:28:59.910 --> 00:29:01.710
those sections in your presentation.

00:29:04.590 --> 00:29:08.460
Unique slide titles are
a very, very important thing

00:29:08.461 --> 00:29:10.021
for accessible presentations.

00:29:10.501 --> 00:29:14.520
You must have unique descriptive titles
on each slide even if they're not visible

00:29:14.521 --> 00:29:17.071
but that is not advisable best practice.

00:29:17.100 --> 00:29:19.400
Visible headings are always
the best way to go.

00:29:20.579 --> 00:29:22.829
Screen reader users might rely
on the slide titles

00:29:22.829 --> 00:29:26.041
to know which slide they're on
and to know whether they've moved on

00:29:26.041 --> 00:29:28.771
or moved backwards a slide
depending on their command.

00:29:30.290 --> 00:29:32.178
If you're skimming
or using a screen reader,

00:29:32.178 --> 00:29:35.188
they can quickly scan through those titles
as well and go to the slide

00:29:35.188 --> 00:29:36.230
that they want.

00:29:36.780 --> 00:29:39.211
If you've got multiple slides
with the same information,

00:29:39.211 --> 00:29:42.051
consider adding
a "One," a "Continued,"

00:29:42.052 --> 00:29:45.810
or some kind of note on in the slide title
to make it clear that it is

00:29:46.550 --> 00:29:49.300
a different slide
but contains very similar information.

00:29:53.433 --> 00:29:54.957
Some formatting tips for you.

00:29:54.958 --> 00:29:57.104
Now, these are very similar
to the Word ones,

00:29:57.104 --> 00:30:00.381
so there isn't much difference here,
but there is a few more things to think

00:30:00.381 --> 00:30:02.731
about when it comes
to formatting presentations.

00:30:03.111 --> 00:30:05.824
Again, I've got a very grumpy,
angry looking dog

00:30:06.064 --> 00:30:07.604
because these are some of the things

00:30:07.604 --> 00:30:11.029
that I think people forget
about when it comes to presentations,

00:30:11.030 --> 00:30:12.830
but they are still really important.

00:30:13.521 --> 00:30:15.981
Using a readable font is very important.

00:30:16.330 --> 00:30:18.140
Be generous with your spacing still.

00:30:18.171 --> 00:30:20.671
Don't make slides
that are packed with information.

00:30:20.900 --> 00:30:23.200
Make sure there's
enough space between content.

00:30:23.661 --> 00:30:24.920
Don't use transitions,

00:30:24.981 --> 00:30:27.950
keep links short and descriptive,
be mindful of your jargon,

00:30:28.310 --> 00:30:31.160
and as we've said, make sure
your slide titles are unique.

00:30:31.940 --> 00:30:34.250
They're quite specific
to PowerPoint in some ways,

00:30:34.250 --> 00:30:36.471
because if you're presenting
this information,

00:30:36.471 --> 00:30:37.771
the text has got to be big

00:30:37.861 --> 00:30:41.070
and you've got to make sure
that you're presenting information

00:30:41.071 --> 00:30:43.911
in a way that's quick,
easy and easy to digest.

00:30:44.770 --> 00:30:46.851
Sometimes they're overlooked
when creating PowerPoints

00:30:46.851 --> 00:30:49.401
because there's so many other things
to think about.

00:30:51.070 --> 00:30:54.051
One final tip I would give
if you are creating presentations,

00:30:54.051 --> 00:30:55.801
just think about your use of color.

00:30:56.781 --> 00:30:59.210
Don't use color on its own
to specify anything.

00:31:00.021 --> 00:31:02.566
If you're giving a presentation,
be mindful that people

00:31:02.566 --> 00:31:05.516
are going to be experiencing
those slides in different ways.

00:31:05.810 --> 00:31:09.649
On this slide I have two circles;
one is red and the other is red

00:31:09.650 --> 00:31:10.650
with the letter A.

00:31:11.691 --> 00:31:14.330
To avoid indicating with color alone,

00:31:15.741 --> 00:31:16.940
if you say something like,

00:31:16.940 --> 00:31:17.916
"Highlighted in red is--"

00:31:17.917 --> 00:31:19.010
not everyone's going to know

00:31:19.010 --> 00:31:21.080
what that is or where it is on the slide.

00:31:21.830 --> 00:31:24.951
Instead I would say, "Labelled
with letter A and colored red."

00:31:25.720 --> 00:31:29.621
There may be some people in your audience
who are not viewing the screen at all.

00:31:29.621 --> 00:31:32.671
Send the slides in advance,
so having those short descriptions

00:31:32.811 --> 00:31:35.361
is also really, really helpful
in the notes section.

