00:32:45.411 --> 00:32:49.941
On the first sheet, Cell A1
can be used to give a workbook summary.

00:32:50.301 --> 00:32:54.291
As described in the previous section,
that's how that cell can be used.

00:32:55.632 --> 00:32:59.930
On any worksheet, Cell A1 can also be used
for the title of the table that follows.

00:33:00.440 --> 00:33:03.470
It very much depends
on how big your spreadsheet is

00:33:03.711 --> 00:33:07.092
and how you've set it up
as to how you might use Cell A1.

00:33:10.370 --> 00:33:12.471
Name your sheets and name your tables.

00:33:12.770 --> 00:33:16.370
It's important that you name your file
and name your worksheets in Excel.

00:33:17.201 --> 00:33:21.356
By default, worksheets
are normally named sheet 1, sheet 2,

00:33:21.676 --> 00:33:23.959
but you should rename these
and give them some more

00:33:23.959 --> 00:33:25.010
of a meaningful name.

00:33:25.780 --> 00:33:26.780
Why is that?

00:33:26.781 --> 00:33:30.331
Well, that just helps the user know
what the information is inside them.

00:33:30.651 --> 00:33:32.120
As with any application,

00:33:32.121 --> 00:33:34.730
it's important that tables
are properly created

00:33:34.940 --> 00:33:37.370
with correctly marked up header rows
and columns,

00:33:37.371 --> 00:33:40.371
very much like we said
about using them in a normal document.

00:33:41.031 --> 00:33:43.880
However, you can convert
data into an accessible table

00:33:43.881 --> 00:33:45.581
which makes it easier to navigate.

00:33:47.240 --> 00:33:49.341
If you want to give
your table a descriptive name,

00:33:49.341 --> 00:33:52.341
normally under the table tab there'll be
a section that says,

00:33:52.641 --> 00:33:53.641
"Table Name."

00:33:53.961 --> 00:33:55.811
Make sure you add something in there.

00:33:56.960 --> 00:33:59.990
The more descriptive the better
as with all of these things.

00:34:05.111 --> 00:34:07.615
No blanking, no merging.

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:09.679
Do not merge or split cells.

00:34:09.680 --> 00:34:10.790
Very similar to what we,

00:34:10.790 --> 00:34:13.551
again, discussed in a Word document,
for example.

00:34:13.851 --> 00:34:16.641
It creates an irregular pattern
and can make the data quite hard

00:34:16.641 --> 00:34:17.641
to understand.

00:34:18.742 --> 00:34:21.221
Screen reader users
might often count table cells

00:34:21.222 --> 00:34:22.971
to keep track of their location,

00:34:22.979 --> 00:34:26.511
so when you nest tables,
you merge or split cells,

00:34:26.831 --> 00:34:29.600
it can be hard to keep count
and that doesn't really provide

00:34:29.600 --> 00:34:30.921
much helpful information.

00:34:32.091 --> 00:34:35.449
It's recommended that any blank cells
are replaced with something.

00:34:35.450 --> 00:34:40.520
We don't like to leave cells blank,
so either an NA for not applicable,

00:34:40.550 --> 00:34:41.991
or a dash, or a hyphen.

00:34:42.291 --> 00:34:46.101
Again, that one's not necessarily the best
because it can have multiple meanings,

00:34:46.101 --> 00:34:47.951
but maybe even putting zero in there,

00:34:48.380 --> 00:34:50.960
if it's a budget sheet,
