00:40:38.680 --> 00:40:41.289
As I say, I don't know
much about any of them.

00:40:41.290 --> 00:40:43.191
I just know they exist.

00:40:43.300 --> 00:40:45.219
Host: All right. Thank you so much.

00:40:45.220 --> 00:40:48.156
Then we have a couple from Claire [?]

00:40:48.310 --> 00:40:52.991
If an image in a document
is decorative, what should you do?

00:40:53.870 --> 00:40:55.689
Samantha: Yes, really good question.

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:57.249
It can be tackled
in a couple of ways.

00:40:57.250 --> 00:40:59.469
There is a mark decorative box.

00:40:59.470 --> 00:41:01.939
However, I always try and steer
people away from using that

00:41:01.940 --> 00:41:05.649
because I think an image
will always normally have a purpose.

00:41:05.650 --> 00:41:07.869
You will have put
it in there for some reason.

00:41:07.870 --> 00:41:09.609
For example,
if you talk about healthy eating

00:41:09.610 --> 00:41:10.899
and you've got a picture of an apple,

00:41:10.900 --> 00:41:12.129
you've put
it in there because you think

00:41:12.130 --> 00:41:14.409
that's an example
of something healthy to eat.

00:41:14.410 --> 00:41:16.979
I would probably describe
that so people get an understanding

00:41:16.980 --> 00:41:20.889
about what you mean when you say
healthy eating in your context.

00:41:20.890 --> 00:41:24.189
There's very few instances
where images are purely decorative.

00:41:24.190 --> 00:41:25.379
If I'm using a logo,

00:41:25.380 --> 00:41:28.089
it's because I want to make sure that
people know that document is owned

00:41:28.090 --> 00:41:30.549
by that organization, for example.

00:41:30.550 --> 00:41:32.709
Always consider
how decorative it really is.

00:41:32.710 --> 00:41:36.339
If you really don't think
it adds any extra value, one,

00:41:36.340 --> 00:41:37.899
maybe consider removing it.

00:41:37.900 --> 00:41:40.539
If you really do think it should
be there, then maybe add some,

00:41:40.540 --> 00:41:43.179
you can tick the mark
as decorative box, but we really,

00:41:43.180 --> 00:41:47.109
really use that in cases
where there's really no added value

00:41:47.110 --> 00:41:48.309
to adding a description at all,

00:41:48.310 --> 00:41:51.801
which in most cases
is quite rare, I believe.

00:41:52.150 --> 00:41:55.179
But that box is always
there if you need to use it.

00:41:55.180 --> 00:41:56.299
Host: All right, thank you.

00:41:56.300 --> 00:42:01.960
Then the next question is,
you said don't use underline

00:42:01.980 --> 00:42:06.185
in documents, but is this
not best practice for links?

00:42:06.670 --> 00:42:07.619
Samantha: Absolutely.

00:42:07.620 --> 00:42:09.089
Apologies if that came
over in the wrong way.

00:42:09.090 --> 00:42:11.739
That's not what I intended
at all from that comment.

00:42:11.740 --> 00:42:13.419
Links should always be underlined.

00:42:13.420 --> 00:42:15.619
The reason why we don't
underline anything else

00:42:15.620 --> 00:42:16.939
is for the reason that people

00:42:16.940 --> 00:42:19.899
can then hopefully
identify links with ease.

00:42:19.900 --> 00:42:22.819
If we just keep underline
limited to underlining links,

00:42:22.820 --> 00:42:24.639
then people can scan documents

00:42:24.640 --> 00:42:27.369
and find that information
visually quite easily.

00:42:27.370 --> 00:42:29.679
If we start underlining other things,
you might try and click

00:42:29.680 --> 00:42:32.169
on it because you assume
it's probably a link and it's not,

00:42:32.170 --> 00:42:33.669
and it can just get
a little bit confusing.

00:42:33.670 --> 00:42:34.899
So yes, absolutely.

00:42:34.900 --> 00:42:38.059
Keep your underline for links,
but links only.

00:42:38.060 --> 00:42:40.509
Host: Thank you
for the clarification.

00:42:40.510 --> 00:42:42.880
From Kwaku, we have,

00:42:43.240 --> 00:42:46.599
what's the single most common
accessibility mistake you see

00:42:46.600 --> 00:42:50.529
in digital documents
and how could someone quickly fix it?

00:42:50.530 --> 00:42:54.642
And what's one tip for a beginner
that beginners often overlook

00:42:54.643 --> 00:42:58.289
that can make document
instantly more accessible?

00:42:58.290 --> 00:42:59.179
Samantha: Yes, I love this question.

00:42:59.180 --> 00:43:00.519
There's quite a lot in there,
but actually

00:43:00.520 --> 00:43:03.279
it's probably one answer
that can answer all of it.

00:43:03.280 --> 00:43:05.289
I think for me,
the most common mistake

00:43:05.290 --> 00:43:07.739
is headings or lack
of heading structure.

00:43:07.740 --> 00:43:09.819
People are often,
through no fault of their own,

00:43:09.820 --> 00:43:11.529
because they don't realize
it's there,

00:43:11.530 --> 00:43:13.509
not make something
a heading through formatting

00:43:13.510 --> 00:43:16.659
and just make it size 25,
bold, and say, look,

00:43:16.660 --> 00:43:18.299
visually that looks like a heading.

00:43:18.300 --> 00:43:20.409
Yes, you're not wrong,
it does, but actually

00:43:20.410 --> 00:43:22.629
from a formatting
and accessibility perspective,

00:43:22.630 --> 00:43:25.269
that doesn't help
the structure of the document,

00:43:25.270 --> 00:43:29.350
makes it really hard to navigate
and gives it no kind of structure

00:43:29.351 --> 00:43:31.839
or easy to navigable
table of contents either,

00:43:31.840 --> 00:43:34.731
which is really
important for documents.

00:43:34.732 --> 00:43:36.729
The same goes
for a presentation as well.

00:43:36.730 --> 00:43:39.745
Every slide should need
a unique title.

00:43:39.940 --> 00:43:41.799
That's effectively
a heading in a document.

00:43:41.800 --> 00:43:42.789
There's no difference really,

00:43:42.790 --> 00:43:45.439
it's just the way
that the documents are set out.

00:43:45.440 --> 00:43:47.409
For me, the most common
mistake is no headings,

00:43:47.410 --> 00:43:50.239
which then means that you
don't have a good table of contents.

00:43:50.240 --> 00:43:51.459
You can't navigate easily.

00:43:51.460 --> 00:43:53.379
The knock-on effects
of that are quite wide.

00:43:53.380 --> 00:43:55.599
If you just add headings,
you've instantly made

00:43:55.600 --> 00:43:59.179
your document much easier
to make your way through.

00:43:59.180 --> 00:44:00.999
So if you're a beginner in this space

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:02.619
and you're a little bit overwhelmed,

00:44:02.620 --> 00:44:04.232
there was quite a lot
in that presentation

00:44:04.233 --> 00:44:05.699
because I wanted to try and get

00:44:05.700 --> 00:44:07.329
across quite a bit
in a short amount of time.

00:44:07.330 --> 00:44:10.359
But I think
alternative text and adding

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:12.099
in headings are really crucial,

00:44:12.100 --> 00:44:14.259
and if you do that throughout
your document,

00:44:14.260 --> 00:44:16.029
as a beginner,
you can make a big impact

00:44:16.030 --> 00:44:19.839
on the final accessible
output in a way that other tips

00:44:19.840 --> 00:44:22.776
might not have as overarching effect.

00:44:23.410 --> 00:44:24.849
Host: Thank you so much.

00:44:24.850 --> 00:44:26.668
We have one from Taco.

00:44:27.610 --> 00:44:30.670
How accessible are the generated PDF

00:44:30.760 --> 00:44:33.189
versions of PowerPoint slide decks?

00:44:33.190 --> 00:44:35.920
Is Google Sheets better or worse?

00:44:38.680 --> 00:44:40.719
Samantha: They're not very accessible
is the short answer

00:44:40.720 --> 00:44:43.029
to that, which helps
to keep it simple.

00:44:43.030 --> 00:44:45.519
But yes, PowerPoint slides

00:44:45.520 --> 00:44:49.179
that are converted to PDF,
the two document types

00:44:49.180 --> 00:44:50.439
were never meant to be compatible.

00:44:50.440 --> 00:44:52.809
PowerPoints are used
for presentations.

00:44:52.810 --> 00:44:55.000
It's very unlikely that
they are ever produced

00:44:55.001 --> 00:44:58.239
to be in PDF format because PDFs
have a very different use case.

00:44:58.240 --> 00:45:00.849
It's not impossible
to make them accessible,

00:45:00.850 --> 00:45:03.039
but it's not very easy at all,

00:45:03.040 --> 00:45:05.112
especially if you've got
extra bits in there,

00:45:05.113 --> 00:45:08.289
like images and lots
of other things in a PowerPoint deck,

00:45:08.290 --> 00:45:09.369
which you probably would have

00:45:09.370 --> 00:45:11.739
because that's how PowerPoints
are normally designed.

00:45:11.740 --> 00:45:15.159
Making that accessible in PDF
format can be quite tricky.

00:45:15.160 --> 00:45:18.729
Google Slides, Google,
any kind of Google product,

00:45:18.730 --> 00:45:20.949
again, I don't think
it's any particularly better.

00:45:20.950 --> 00:45:22.799
I think it's always
going to be problematic

00:45:22.800 --> 00:45:25.629
converting a presentation into a PDF.

00:45:25.630 --> 00:45:29.121
The two are just not
going to work very well.

00:45:29.290 --> 00:45:30.669
Host: Thank you. Thank you for that.

00:45:30.670 --> 00:45:35.109
Again, I'm learning something
as I'm asking these questions.

00:45:35.110 --> 00:45:39.129
From Isabel, do you think
that the accessibility checker

00:45:39.130 --> 00:45:44.049
of PowerPoint is helpful for making
an accessible presentation?

00:45:44.800 --> 00:45:45.579
Samantha: Absolutely.

00:45:45.580 --> 00:45:47.199
I always, always, always,

00:45:47.200 --> 00:45:49.359
and in any kind of product
where you've got

00:45:49.360 --> 00:45:52.454
an accessibility checker,
please use it.

00:45:52.750 --> 00:45:55.750
We always say that don't rely on it.

00:45:56.380 --> 00:45:58.629
I always say to people,
it's your starting point.

00:45:58.630 --> 00:46:00.189
When you've finished,
you've got your document ready,

00:46:00.190 --> 00:46:02.919
you think it's good to go,
run the checker on it,

00:46:02.920 --> 00:46:04.639
and then action anything
that comes out of that.

00:46:04.640 --> 00:46:07.359
But then there's a few more manual
checks that you also need to do.

00:46:07.360 --> 00:46:09.221
So it won't cover everything.

00:46:09.222 --> 00:46:12.303
For example, it doesn't check
all types of color contrast.

00:46:12.304 --> 00:46:14.709
It will check if you've got
bright red text

00:46:14.710 --> 00:46:17.799
in a white background or something
that's kind of more obvious

00:46:17.800 --> 00:46:19.569
when it comes to color contrast.

00:46:19.570 --> 00:46:21.039
But if you're using two blues

00:46:21.040 --> 00:46:24.039
that are just slightly off contrast
when it comes to the ratios,

00:46:24.040 --> 00:46:25.749
it wouldn't necessarily pick that up,

00:46:25.750 --> 00:46:27.459
so therefore you checking
that manually

00:46:27.460 --> 00:46:29.259
is gonna give you the best result.

00:46:29.260 --> 00:46:30.539
Similarly, if you've got links

00:46:30.540 --> 00:46:32.319
in your presentation
or your document,

00:46:32.320 --> 00:46:34.099
and you've just put them in as URLs,

00:46:34.100 --> 00:46:36.459
it's not going to pick up
that's an accessibility issue,

00:46:36.460 --> 00:46:39.039
but that really
is an accessibility problem

00:46:39.040 --> 00:46:41.949
that we would need
to check through manually.

00:46:41.950 --> 00:46:43.419
The checkers are brilliant.

00:46:43.420 --> 00:46:46.019
If you're a beginner in this space,
they often explain

00:46:46.020 --> 00:46:49.139
why it's a problem and how to fix it,
which is brilliant.

00:46:49.140 --> 00:46:52.419
But don't rely on them alone
because they don't cover everything

00:46:52.420 --> 00:46:54.205
and they will miss bits.

00:46:54.206 --> 00:46:56.819
So you will always be more
powerful than the checker,

00:46:56.820 --> 00:46:59.079
which is what I like to tell people.

00:46:59.080 --> 00:47:00.019
Host: All right, thank you.

00:47:00.020 --> 00:47:01.020
Thank you.

00:47:01.660 --> 00:47:04.629
And we have one final
question from Sally.

00:47:04.630 --> 00:47:08.359
Does compressing a PDF
affect its accessibility?

00:47:09.400 --> 00:47:10.599
Samantha: This is a great question

00:47:10.600 --> 00:47:12.410
and unfortunately
I can't say yes or no,

00:47:12.411 --> 00:47:13.809
or give a really point blank answer

00:47:13.810 --> 00:47:16.629
because it depends
on how the compression is done

00:47:16.630 --> 00:47:19.629
and what elements are removed
when it is compressed.

00:47:19.630 --> 00:47:22.359
Often compressing
a PDF will flatten it.

00:47:22.360 --> 00:47:24.399
It will turn the text
and structure into images,

00:47:24.400 --> 00:47:27.789
which can obviously remove tags,
reading order or text,

00:47:27.790 --> 00:47:29.319
some of that interactive
elements if you've got

00:47:29.320 --> 00:47:31.479
form fields and things
like that in there.

00:47:31.480 --> 00:47:33.219
It can also remove embedded fonts,

00:47:33.220 --> 00:47:36.039
which can cause
problems for accessibility.

00:47:36.040 --> 00:47:40.749
And some third party tools that
compress them can remove metadata

00:47:40.750 --> 00:47:42.339
to try and reduce file size,

00:47:42.340 --> 00:47:45.752
which removes titles
and authors, et cetera.

00:47:46.780 --> 00:47:47.679
My best advice,

00:47:47.680 --> 00:47:50.539
if you do need to compress
a PDF file is do it and then use

00:47:50.540 --> 00:47:52.809
a tool like your
Adobe Acrobat, your PAC,

00:47:52.810 --> 00:47:55.629
whatever it is you use
to check accessibility,

00:47:55.630 --> 00:47:58.219
to check what it looks
like after you've compressed it,

00:47:58.220 --> 00:48:00.819
and then you might need
to add some of those bits back in

00:48:00.820 --> 00:48:03.519
because those things are fundamental
for an accessible PDF.

00:48:03.520 --> 00:48:06.559
We can't ignore
that they need to be in there.

00:48:06.560 --> 00:48:10.859
Don't let it affect
the accessibility of your final file.

